{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}} {{Use British English|date=April 2018}} Prof. '''Bernard Richards''' [[British Computer Society|FBCS]], [[Institute of Mathematics and its Applications|FIMA]], [[Institute for Health Record and Information Management|FIHRIM]], [[Russian Academy of Medical Sciences|FRAMS]] is a British [[computer scientist]] and an Emeritus Professor of [[Medical Informatics]] at the [[University of Manchester]], England.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.manchester.ac.uk/research/bernard.richards/ | title=Prof Bernard Richards – personal details | publisher=[[The University of Manchester]] | accessdate=23 January 2018 }}</ref>
Richards studied mathematics and physics for his bachelor's degree.<ref name="copeland17">{{cite book| authorlink=Jack Copeland | last1=Copeland | first1=Jack | authorlink2=Jonathan Bowen | last2=Bowen | first2=Jonathan | last3=Sprevak | first3=Mark | authorlink4=Robin Wilson (mathematician) | last4=Wilson | first4=Robin | author5=et al. | title=[[The Turing Guide]] | publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] | year=2017 | isbn=978-0198747833 | pages=478 | chapter=Notes on Contributors }}</ref> For his master's degree, he worked under the supervision of [[Alan Turing]] (1912–1954) at Manchester as one of Turing's last students, helping to validate Turing’s theory of [[morphogenesis]].<ref>{{cite| last=Richards | first=Bernard | year=1954 | title=The Morphogenesis of Radiolaria | work=MSc thesis | publisher=[[The University of Manchester]] | location=Manchester, UK }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| last=Richards | first=Bernard | year=2005 | title=Turing, Richards and morphogenesis | journal=[[The Rutherford Journal]] | volume=1 | url=http://www.rutherfordjournal.org/article010109.html }}</ref><ref>{{cite book| last=Richards | first=Bernard | year=2017 | chapter=Chapter 35 – Radiolaria: Validating the Turing theory | editor-last1=Copeland | editor-first1=Jack |editorlink1=Jack Copeland | editor2=et al. | title=[[The Turing Guide]] | pages=383–388 }}</ref> Reflecting on Turing's death at the age of 80 during Turing's centenary year in 2012, Richards commented: "The day he died felt like driving through a tunnel and the lights being switched off".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/alan-turing-the-day-he-died-689846 | title=Alan Turing: ‘The day he died felt like driving through a tunnel and the lights being switched off’ | newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]] | date=19 June 2012 | accessdate=23 January 2018 | first=David | last=Henry }}</ref>
After Turing died, Richards changed his research area and worked for his doctorate, studying an aspect of [[optics]], resulting in a [[Royal Society]] paper with his supervisor, Professor [[Emil Wolf]].<ref name="copeland17" /> This provided a detailed description of the diffraction of light through a [[convex lens]]. After this, Richards moved into the area of medicine, producing an important paper on hormone peaks in the [[menstrual cycle]]. Later he worked on [[expert system]]s aimed at use in [[open heart surgery]] and also [[intensive care unit]]s.
Richards became Professor of [[Medical Informatics]] at Manchester University and latterly Emeritus Professor within the School of Computer Science.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cs.manchester.ac.uk/about-us/staff/profile/?ea=bernard.richards | title=Prof Bernard Richards – personal details | publisher=School of Computer Science, [[The University of Manchester]] | accessdate=23 January 2018 }}</ref>
Richards has been Chairman of the [[British Computer Society|BCS]] Health Informatics Committee and in 1998 was made BCS Fellow of the Year for Services to Medical Informatics.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bcs.org/upload/pdf/brichards_efmi_statement.pdf | title=My Statement re EFMI Rep | publisher=[[British Computer Society|BCS]] |first=Bernard | last=Richards | accessdate=23 January 2018 }}</ref> He was the first President of the [[Institute for Health Record and Information Management]] (IHRIM), a member of the [[International Federation of Records Officers]] (IFRO). In [[Europe]], he is an Honorary Member of the [[Ukrainian Association for Computer Medicine]] of the [[Ukraine]], the [[Romania]]n Academy of Medical Science, the [[John von Neumann Computer Society]] of [[Hungary]], the [[Czech Republic|Czech]] Medical Informatics Society, and the [[Poland|Polish]] Medical Informatics Society. Richards was presented with an award by [[Queen Elizabeth II]] for contributing a morphogenesis memento to a [[time capsule]] during 2012, Alan Turing's centenary year.<ref>{{cite new| url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/the-northerner/2013/jan/22/alan-turing-computing | title=Alan Turing Year – the Establishment still doesn't get it | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | authorlink=S. Barry Cooper | first=S. Barry | last=Cooper | date=22 January 2013 }}</ref>
